b'' b': b': xmdrawingarea for drawing with xlib. but i would like to take advantage of' b": the graphics library (gl) available on our ibm rs/6000 (sgi's gl i believe)." b': is it possible to mix x and gl in one application program?' b': can i use gl subroutines in an xmdrawingarea or in an x window opened by me' b': with xopenwindow?' b'' b"you can't make gl calls in an xmdrawingarea widget for sure." b':' b': there is a widget already defined for gl. it is the glxmdraw (motif) or' b': glxdraw (athena) widget. it is similar to a xmdrawingarea, except that it' b': allows you to use gl calls to render into the window. look at glxlink,' b': glxunlink, glxgetconfig, and glxwinset in the man pages.' b':' b':' b': the glxmdraw widget works pretty well. opengl will be an improvement.' b'' b'i can vouch for that. the gl widget works pretty well. i have been using it' b"for sometime now. i'm not sure though whether you can use xlib calls to draw" b"into the gl widget. i haven't tried it yet nor have i read the accompanying" b'documentation completely. try posting to comp.sys.sgi for more information.' b'better still,you will find most of the answers in the sgi manuals there' b'is a little transition guide which explains the "mixed-model programming"' b'paradigm(mixing x and gl).' b'' b': does pex (graphigs?) have the same functionality of gl?' b':' b': i think gl is a little easier to use and a little more powerful, but' b": that's just an opinion. mileage may vary." b'' b'well, pex is designed as an extension to x and will be more seamless but' b'then, it is buggy to start with opinions again.' b'' b'__' b'(_ o_ o o b'__)/(_( b'' b'***************************************************************************' b'* institute of systems science tel: b'* national university of singapore facs.: b'* heng mui keng terrace telex: issnus rs b'* singapore b'***************************************************************************' 